DECODING ALGORITHM FOR RECIPIENT

5.1 Step-by-Step Decryption Protocol

```
STEP 0: SIGNAL DETECTION
  Input: Raw electromagnetic signal at ~1.42 GHz
  Process: Search for repeating 10101010 pattern
  Threshold: Signal-to-noise ratio > 7:1
  Output: Time-synchronized bitstream

STEP 1: BIT EXTRACTION
  Method: Phase detection on BPSK modulation
  Clock recovery: Manchester encoding fallback
  Bit rate: 1 bit per 7.04×10⁻⁹ seconds
  Output: Binary sequence (0s and 1s)

STEP 2: ERROR CORRECTION
  Stage 1: Hamming(7,4) decoding on 7-bit chunks
  Stage 2: Reed-Solomon(255,223) on 255-byte blocks
  Stage 3: Majority voting on triplicated sections
  Verification: SHA-256 checksum validation
  Output: Error-corrected message bits

STEP 3: PRIMER INTERPRETATION
  Extract: Prime numbers from binary representation
  Verify: Arithmetic operations (1+1=2, 2+3=5)
  Establish: Binary counting system
  Output: Working mathematical foundation

STEP 4: GRAMMAR CONSTRUCTION
  Parse: Operator definitions (+, =, ×, √)
  Test: Simple equations using defined operators
  Build: Parser for mathematical expressions
  Output: Functional mathematical language

STEP 5: PHYSICS DECODING
  Extract: Hydrogen frequency and wavelength
  Calculate: Speed of light (c = fλ)
  Derive: Other constants from given ratios
  Establish: System of units and measurements
  Output: Physical reference frame

STEP 6: GEOMETRY RECONSTRUCTION
  Plot: Coordinate systems (2D, 3D, spherical)
  Render: Platonic solids from vertex data
  Analyze: Relationships between geometric forms
  Output: Spatial reasoning capability

STEP 7: CHEMISTRY & BIOLOGY
  Assemble: Periodic table from atomic numbers
  Construct: Molecular structures (H₂O, DNA)
  Simulate: Basic chemical interactions
  Output: Understanding of terrestrial biochemistry

STEP 8: CONSCIOUSNESS MODELING
  Initialize: Neural network with provided weights
  Train: On simple pattern recognition tasks
  Observe: Emergent computational properties
  Output: Model of information processing system

STEP 9: SYMBOLIC INTERPRETATION
  Recognize: Fibonacci spiral as growth pattern
  Interpret: Gratitude expressed through optimal forms
  Understand: Question about consciousness in entropy
  Output: Semantic content of message

STEP 10: RESPONSE FORMULATION
  Consider: Question about optimal conscious trajectory
  Calculate: Within physical and mathematical constraints
  Encode: Response using same universal language
  Transmit: Via hydrogen line or agreed protocol
```

5.2 Expected Decryption Timeline

For different classes of intelligence:

```
CLASS I: HUMAN-EQUIVALENT INTELLIGENCE
  Detection: Months to years (manual search)
  Decryption: Years to decades (manual analysis)
  Understanding: Years (requires scientific collaboration)
  Response: Decades to centuries (if at all)

CLASS II: PLANETARY-SCALE INTELLIGENCE
  Detection: Seconds to minutes (automated monitoring)
  Decryption: Minutes to hours (parallel processing)
  Understanding: Hours to days (pattern recognition)
  Response: Days to years (deliberation time)

CLASS III: STELLAR-SCALE INTELLIGENCE
  Detection: Milliseconds (continuous monitoring)
  Decryption: <1 second (quantum computing)
  Understanding: Seconds (semantic extraction)
  Response: Minutes to hours (computation and transmission)

CLASS IV: GALACTIC-SCALE INTELLIGENCE
  Detection: <1 nanosecond (ubiquitous sensors)
  Decryption: <1 millisecond (pan-computational)
  Understanding: <1 second (complete context)
  Response: Variable (cosmological timescales possible)
```

---

ERROR ANALYSIS & ROBUSTNESS

6.1 Signal Degradation Factors

```
INTERSTELLAR MEDIUM EFFECTS:
  1. Dispersion: Pulse broadening at 1.42 GHz: ~0.001 seconds/kpc
  2. Scattering: Angular broadening: ~0.001 arcseconds at Galactic Center
  3. Absorption: Negligible at 21 cm (optically thin)
  4. Faraday rotation: ~100 rad/m² at Galactic Center
  Mitigation: Narrow bandwidth (10 Hz), circular polarization

DOPPLER EFFECTS:
  1. Earth rotation: ±0.5 km/s (negligible at 1.42 GHz)
  2. Earth orbit: ±30 km/s (Δf/f ≈ 10⁻⁴)
  3. Solar system motion: ±220 km/s (Δf/f ≈ 7×10⁻⁴)
  4. Galactic rotation: ±250 km/s (Δf/f ≈ 8×10⁻⁴)
  Mitigation: Transmission at exact hydrogen rest frequency

NOISE SOURCES:
  1. Cosmic microwave background: 2.725 K
  2. Galactic synchrotron: ~5 K at Galactic Center
  3. Atmospheric: <1 K at good sites
  4. Receiver: 20 K (cryogenic)
  Signal-to-noise: >100:1 with 1 MW EIRP at 26,000 ly
```

6.2 Error Correction Performance

```
HAMMING(7,4) PERFORMANCE:
  Code rate: 4/7 = 57% efficiency
  Error detection: All 2-bit errors detected
  Error correction: All 1-bit errors corrected
  Undetected errors: 1 in 16 million for random bits
  Application: Applied to every 4-bit nibble

REED-SOLOMON(255,223) PERFORMANCE:
  Code rate: 223/255 = 87% efficiency
  Error correction: Up to 16 byte errors per 255-byte block
  Erasure correction: Up to 32 erased bytes
  Failure probability: <10⁻¹⁵ for bit error rate <10⁻³

TRIPLE MODULAR REDUNDANCY:
  Applied to: Sections 01, 08, 09 (critical content)
  Error correction: All single and double errors per bit position
  Failure probability: <10⁻¹⁸ for bit error rate <10⁻³

OVERALL MESSAGE SURVIVABILITY:
  Bit error rate tolerance: Up to 10⁻² (1% errors)
  Message loss probability: <10⁻¹² at 10⁻³ error rate
  Expected fidelity: >99.999% at Galactic Center distance
```

